	   <tr><td colspan=2>The answer to your question as I understand it is no..... Any trade (or skill for that matter) starts at any level (character level) you start the skill/trade at zero.  You must go to your class's local guild and train in any desired skill/trade.  You are given 5 &quot;skill points&quot; per lvl, and can use these points to train in any skills that you may want, and have available to train in (some do not become available till later levels).  Skills increase with use, but ALL must be given that 1st training point (VERY IMPORTANT).  Some people unload all the training points they get each time into training...  But ALL just need the one to get started.  I usually only use 1 point per skill that I need.  Then you can gauge the ones that go up faster than others and evauluate where you might want to invest the extra points.  Depending on the trade that you choose,  gaining skill levels can be pretty expensive, so you should gage that fact too, in your allocation of your skill points... The first investment of points, though, should be invested in the essential skills your character will need to survive... (i.e. melee skills, spell casting skills, etc..)Most trades can actually be started whenever you want... but you shouldn't waste the points on it until you have the $$$ that many of these trades require in investment in the very beginning (this will also give you a chance to get a feel for the game, and what trades you might be interested in).  One more point I will make before I stop boring you is this... Choose your trade to coincide with your character if you can... ( i.e. Fletching for Rangers, Reseach for casters, etc) this can save you some hassle in the future.  Plus you can only hope to TRUELY master ONE skill... once this one skill is mastered the game will not allow you to gain quite that lvl (like over 200) in ANY other trade you choose.... Do your homework too, because different trades work together to make better items...<br><br>Fleewell 15th lvl druid<br>SoW pimp extrodinare/Master of Getting out of Dodge (thus the name)<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
